Adversarial Thinking (AT) is increasingly recognized as a critical competency for preparing secure, resilient, and ethically grounded computing professionals. This poster presents an experience report from a community college initiative that integrates AT throughout the computer science pathway (CS0–CS3) to strengthen cybersecurity awareness and workforce readiness. The effort centers on two goals: (1) infusing AT into foundational programming courses through updated syllabi, aligned learning outcomes, and AT-focused summative assessments; and (2) expanding experiential learning via peer-led team learning (PLTL), weekly employer-led workshops, and recurring hackathon/datathon events. Evaluation findings indicate gains in student self-efficacy, perceived relevance, and readiness for industry engagement, as well as employer-reported reductions in onboarding time for new hires. Aligned with CS2023 and CSEC2017 guidelines, this work offers a replicable, OER-supported framework for community and technical colleges seeking to embed adversarial thinking within computing curricula.